In 2006, the Nokia 1600 was the top-selling phone in the world, and the Bla=
ckBerry Pearl the best-selling smartphone. Both were only a year away from =
their doom, but that doom was not a cheaper, less-capable product, but in f=
act the exact opposite: a far more powerful, and fantastically more expensi=
ve product called the iPhone.

